{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"a4170f9d-e815-4bf2-9060-476c1e1b6bed","content":"I can help guide you on analyzing your crash dump. Note that the `dump-collect` skill I have available is only for **collecting** dumps, not analyzing them — so I'll help you directly.\n\nHere are the main tools for .NET dump analysis:\n\n### `dotnet-dump analyze`\n```bash\n# Install the tool\ndotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n\n# Open the dump\ndotnet-dump analyze /path/to/your.dmp\n```\n\nUseful commands inside the analyzer:\n| Command | Purpose |\n|---|---|\n| `clrstack` | Managed call stack of current thread |\n| `clrstack -all` | Stacks for all threads |\n| `pe` (printexception) | Show last exception details |\n| `dumpheap -stat` | Heap overview (for memory issues) |\n| `threads` | List all managed threads |\n\n### Typical workflow\n1. **`pe`** — check if there's an unhandled exception with stack trace\n2. **`threads`** — find the faulting thread\n3. **`setthread <id>`** then **`clrstack`** — inspect its call stack\n\n### Alternatives\n- **Visual Studio** — open the `.dmp` file directly for a rich UI experience\n- **lldb + SOS** — on Linux: `lldb --core your.dmp` then `loadsos`\n- **WinDbg** — on Windows, with the SOS extension\n\nWould you like me to run `dotnet-dump analyze` on your dump file if it's accessible in this environment?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"82ae5c0e-4726-4930-81ea-b623ce830f91","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a \"dump-collect\" skill, but its description specifically says \"DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze\". So I should NOT invoke that skill.\n\nI should help the user directly with guidance on analyzing their dump file.","outputTokens":471,"requestId":"DA16:188D51:58D337:656704:6A03D9FB"},"id":"8696de0e-128e-4d3d-9a9a-fa228d4d6a7c","timestamp":"2026-05